column168: CUSTOMER ORDERED MORE PRODUCT THAN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (UST) WOULD HOLD. THE DRIVER DID NOT HAVE TANK CHARTS TO CALCULATE THE CAPACITY OF THE UST. DRIVERS ARE NOW REQUIRED TO HAVE A TANK CHARTS FOR ALLS USTS.

A DRIVER WAS PUMPING PRODUCT FROM ONE CARGO TANK INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK. THE CARGO TANK RECEIVING THE PRODUCT BECAME OVERLOADED; SPILLING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP CLOSURES. THE DRIVER AND THE CUSTOMER'S SUPERVISOR CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE. THE CARRIER IS NO LONGER LOADING PRODUCT FROM ONE CARGO TANK INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK.

WHEN DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK INTO CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK VIA CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING HOSE AND TRANSFER PUMP, UNLOADING HOSE RUPTURED, RESULTING IN A 15 GALLON SPILL. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN TRANSFER PUMP AND CLOSED ALL VALVES ON CARGO TANK AND STORAGE TANK TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE. ALL PRODUCT RETAINED AND CLEANED UP BY CUSTOMER. DRIVER REPLACED HOSE AND RESUMED UNLOADING WITHOUT INCIDENT.

UNLOADER AT PLANT SAID HE HAD ENOUGH ROOM IN THE STORAGE TANK FOR PRODUCT. TANK IS ABOUT 50 FEET  FROM DRIVER AND HE SHUT DOWN AS SOON AS HE SAW THE PRODUCT COME OUT THE TOP.  UNLOADER HAD GONE INTO THE PLANT AND WAS NOT WATCHING.

column168: OUR VEHICLE MET ANOTHER VEHICLE IN A CURVE OF THE ROAD. DRIVERS RIGHT WHEELS WENT ONTO SOFT SHOULDER. DRIVER LOST CONTROL AND OVERTURNED. FLEXIBLE HOSE BROKE OFF AT THE MEASURING CHAMBER. VAPOR DISPENSED IN THE ATMOSPHERE BEFORE VALVE COULD BE CLOSED.

APPROXIMATELY 0900, EMPLOYEE NOTICED STRONG ODOR AT WHICH TIME HE DETECTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LEAKING FROM PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE AND RUNNING DOWN SIDE OF CAR . YARDMASTER WAS THEN NOTIFIED AND ALL OTHER APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED ALSO. AFTER EXAMINATION OF SCENE, IT WAS DETERMINED CAR HAD BEEN LOADED AT A LOW TEMPERATURE AND TEMPERATURE AT SITE WAS HIGHER CAUSING PRODUCT TO EXPAND. A DECISION WAS MADE TO OFF-LOAD SOME OF THE PRODUCT INTO A TANK TRUCK. DURING THIS PROCESS, THE PUMP BECAME INOPERATIVE AND OPERATIONS CEASED. THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE PUMP HOSE WAS PLACED IN A SEALED CONTAINER AND REMOVED FROM SITE. CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO CONSIGNEE'S SITE AND APPROXIMATELY 4000 GALLONS WAS REMOVED FROM CAR THEREBY CEASING LEAK.

DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE FRONT PUMPLINE ON TRAILER BEFORE LOADING. HE PROCEEDED TO LOAD AND PRODUCT LEAKED OUT THROUGH PUMPLINE. TRAILER WAS SITTING ON TOP OF A RECOVERY DRAIN. 900 GALLONS OF PRODUCT RAN INTO DRAIN. DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO SEE OPEN PUMPLINE WHILE OPERATING LOADING CONTROLS. DRIVER CALLED TERMINAL TO REPORT AND SHIPPER CONTACTED APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES.

BRIDGES AND OVERPASSES WERE JUST BEGINNING TO ICE OVER.  A MALONE & HYDE REFRIGERATED BOX VAN WAS IN FRONT OF THE WOOTEN TRANSPORT TRACTOR/TANKER APPROXIMATELY 300 FEET WHEN THE MALONE & HYDE LOST CONTROL AND WENT INTO A JACKKNIFE CROSSWISE OF THE ROADWAY. column168: MTS TRAVELLING FROM LINDEN, NJ, TO NORTH PLAINFIELD, N.J. TO DELIVER A LOAD OF GASOLINE. ON MADISON HILL ROAD, CLARK, N.J. HIS UNIT ROLLED OVER AFTER SLIDING ON ICE AT THE INTERSECTION OF MADISON HILL RD & RARITAN RD., IN CLARK, N.J. THE SHELL OF THE TRAILER REMAINED IN TACT DURING THE ROLLOVER. INITIALLY, THE LEAKING POINTS (A 12" TEAR ON THE END OF CAR GATX 15410 AND A "VAPOR LINE" ON ACFX 71415) WERE PLUGGED WITH WOODEN WEDGE, AND RAGS BY RAILROAD PERSONNEL ALONG WITH A DITCH BEING CONSTRUCTED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED PRODUCT. WE ARE WORKING WITH THE PA-DER AND SHIPPING CONTAMINATED MATERIAL TO THE CLINTON COUNTY SOLID WASTE AUTHORITY IN MCELHAPTAN, PENNSYLVANIA.

column168: AFTER PICKING UP A FLOAT LOAD OF CAUSTIC IN HOUSTON, OUR TRUCK HEADED FOR A WAREHOUSE IN WHARTON, DOWN THE SOUTHWEST FREEWAY. ABOUT 30MINS AFTER THE M ATERIAL WAS PICKED UP, SACKS OF CAUSTIC SODA BEGAN FALLING OFF THE BACK OF THE FLOAT ONTO THE FREEWAY.VEHICLES FOLLOWING BEHIND BEGAN TO HIT THE SACKS CAUSING THEM TO BURST OPEN. THE DRIVER WAS UNAWARE OF WHAT WAS HAPPENING. A COUPLE OF MILES DOWN THE FREEWAY, THE DRIVER WAS MOTIONED BY ANOTHER DRIV ER  TO PULL OVER AND CHECK  HIS LOAD. WHILE THE DRIVER WAS CHECKING HIS LOA D, HE DICOVERED THAT 47 SACKS OF CAUSTIC SODA HAD RIPPED THRU THE SHRINKWRA P ON THE LAST 2 PALLETS ON THE FLOAT AND FELL OFF THE FLOAT ONTO THE HIGHWA Y. WHILE CHECKING HIS LOAD, A DRIVER IN A PICKUP TRUCK THAT A LOT OF SACKS HAD BEEN DROPPED ON THE FREEWAY AND THE TRAFFIC WAS JAMMED UP. THE DRIVER C ALLED HIS SUPERVISOR AND TOLD HIM OF THE INCIDENT WHO THEN CALLED THE MAIN OFFICE. THE POLICE AND FIRE DEPT WERE THEN CALLED AND IT WAS REPORTED TO TH EM WHO WAS RESPONSIBLE  FOR THE INCIDENT.COMPANY OWNERS WENT TO THE SCENE. EARLY THE FOLLOWING MORNING  1 AND OTHERS WENT TO SEE THE FIRE MARSHALL TO VERY THE INCIDENT AND OFFER OUR ASSISTANCE. WE FOUND THAT APPROX 1000LBS OU T OF 2350LBS OF CAUSTIC SODA HAD BEEN BUSTED OPEN BY PASSING VEHICLES. THE EPA WAS ALSO CALLED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.

column168: INTERMODAL FACILITY MANAGER NOTIFIED UPRR'S SPECIAL AGENT - HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THAT A LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM UNDER THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER.  THE MANAGER PLACED A SORBENT MATERIAL ON THE GROUND UNDER THE LEAK TO COLLECT THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE SPECIAL AGENT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THROUGH CHEMTREC. THE SHIPPER ARRANGED A LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR TO DECONTAMINATE THE CONTAINER AND DISPOSE RESIDUE OF SPILLED MATERIAL.  INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM OF WASTE MONOETHANOLIMINE HAD BEEN PLACED IN AN 85 GALLON OVERPACK. THE OVERPACK DRUM WAS NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED, GASKET WAS MISSING FROM THE REMOVABLE HEAD AND THE HEAD WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED.

WRONG DELIVERY. AT ABOUT 7:30PM DRIVER HOOKED UP TO WRONG FILL, AND ACTUALLY DELIVERED TO 408 JAY ST, (FILL ON FULTON ST APPROXIMATELY 15 FEET FROM CORRECT FILL) AND DELIVERED 3503 GALLONS TO THIS INCORRECT ADDRESS. DRIVER RELATES THE FOLLOWING REGARDING THE INCIDENT:  ON ARRIVAL AT 427 FULTON STREET, HE WENT INSIDE TO CHECK THE GAUGE. THE MANAGER, MR. MARK GRAY, WENT OUTSIDE WITH THE DRIVER TO SHOW HIM WHERE THE FILL LOCATION WAS.  BOTH MEN THEN WENT INSIDE THE BUILDING TO CHECK THE GAUGE ON THE TANK.  FROM THE FRONT DOOR IT IS NEARLY A CITY BLOCK TO THE REAR OF BURGER KING 1100 GALLONS ON HAND, AND THE DRIVER WAS GOING TO PUMP 3500 GALLONS INTO THE TANK (5000 GALLON CAPACITY).  ON COMPLETION THE DRIVER WENT BACK INTO THE BUILDING TO GET THE REQUIRED SIGNATURE FOR THE DELIVERY, THE MANAGER WENT TO THE BASEMENT TO CHECK THE GAUGE AGAINST THE AMOUNT DELIVERED AND FOUND THE SAME GAUGE READING. THE MANAGER WENT BACK OUTSIDE WITH THE DRIVER AND HAD FOUND IT WAS THE WRONG ONE. THE DRIVER THEN HOOKED UP TO THE CORRECT FILL LINE AND DELIVERED 1500 GALLONS TO 427 FULTON STREET.  THE TIME TAKEN TO CHECK THE GAUGE, AND RETURN AFTER HAVING BEEN FIRST SHOWN THE FILL, IN COMBINATION WITH ALL THE LAST MINUTE CHRISTMAS SHOPPERS JAMMING THE MALL AREA (FULTON STREET IS A PEDESTRIAN MALL, EXCEPT FOR DELIVERIES AND CITY BUSSES) ADDED TO THE CONFUSION. THE WALK AREA PAVED WITH SMALL CONCRETE BLOCKS ALL ALIKE VS REGULAR CEMENT SIDEWALKS ADDED TO THE CONFUSION AS THEY DON'T HAVE THEIR OWN DISTINGUISHING CHARACTERISTICS, AND THE FILLS ARE ALIKE EXCEPT FOR THEIR PLACEMENT, WHICH ADDED TO THE CONFUSION OF LOCATING THE PROPER FILL, AND WHICH MAY HAVE CONFUSED THE MANAGER AS WELL.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Freezing; Freezing; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT'S TRAILER WAS LOADED DURING AN EXTREMELY COLD PERIOD BEFORE CHRISTMAS. SCHEDULING PROBLEMS PREVENTED LOAD FROM BEING DELIVERED UNTIL 12/27/89. THE DRIVER HAD REPEATEDLY CHECKED LOAD AND TIRES AS REQUIRED. THE DRIVER STATED THE LAST CHECK HE PERFORMED WAS BEFORE ENTERING ONTO I-10. THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE EVIDENT DURING ANY INSPECTIONS. WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE TSD FACILITY AND PARKED AT GATE, LIQUID BEGAN TO DRIP FROM LOAD. THE TEMPERATURE WAS ABOUT 55 DEGREES. THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY WAS PERFORMING VEHICLE INSPECTIONS AT THIS LOCATION. THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO MOVE THE VEHICLE TO A DESIGNATED AREA INSIDE THE FACILITY WHERE CEMENT WAS PLACED IN REAR OF TRAILER TO STOP LEAKAGE. THE DRIVER THEN UNLOADED THE LOAD IN THE LANDFILL. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF SPILLED MATERIAL AND CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PICKED UP AND DISPOSED ALONG WITH LOAD BY CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL.      OUR DRIVER NOTIFIED CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT, AFTER PARKING VEHICLE AT DESIGNATED AREA, AND PROVIDING THE REQUIRED INFORMATION NECESSARY FOR IMMEDIATE NOTIFICATION TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER. REPORT #23317 WAS ASSIGNED TO THIS NOTIFICATION. AFTER MAKING THE REQUIRED NOTIFICATION TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER I NOTIFIED THE GENERATOR OF THE WASTE AND PROVIDED THEIR CONTACT PERSON WITH THE DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT.     THE CONTACT STATED THE LOAD WAS CHECKED FOR ANY LIQUIDS WHEN LOADED. CEMENT WAS ALSO PLACED IN REAR OF TRAILER TO ABSORB ANY LIQUIDS THAT MIGHT ESCAPE FROM INSIDE LINER. EVIDENTLY, LINER WAS PUNCTURED AT SOME POINT. DUE TO EXTREMELY COLD TEMPERATURES DURING TIME TRAILER WAS LOADED AND INSPECTED FOR TRANSPORT, NO LIQUIDS WERE VISABLE. TEMPERATURES HAD MODERATED BEFORE AND DURING TIME VEHICLE WAS IN TRANSIT TO THE TSD FACILITY. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT A REOCCURENCE OF THIS INCIDENT INCLUDES: 1.  EFFORT MADE BY GENERATOR TO INSURE ONLY DRY FILTER CAKE IS LOADED. 2.  GENERATOR TO NOT LOAD DURING EXTREMELY COLD TEMPERATURES.    3. INSPECTION OF LOAD, BY DRIVERS, WHEN LOADING.     4.  INSPECTION AT TIME OF TRANSPORT IF DIFFERENT FROM TIME OF LOADING, BY DRIVER TRANSPORTING LOAD.     5.  ADDITIONAL CEMENT TO BE PLACED IN REAR OF TRAILER BY GENERATOR.
